@node "lists" "lists"

The show button determinates what is being showed in the Listview.
Maby you better use Cycle2Menu with you workbench as there are 11 items
to cycle through.

There is always an item selected in a list.
The selected item (for each list)is saved in the .ezmke file
and is reselected when loaded.


   @{b}@{u}File lists@{ub}@{uu}
   @{"Sources" LINK "ls_source"}
   @{"Executables" LINK "ls_exec"}


   @{b}@{u}Command Lists@{ub}@{uu}
   
   In these lists you put commands which are executed one by one.
   The following words have special meanings:
     %s -Current selected source in the source-list
         NOTE: EZMake selects sources on its own when using the MAKE button.
     %o -Objectname
         Same as %s but with any suffix removed and @{"objectsuffix" LINK "objectsuffix"} added.
     %l -Linker names
         Object names of all sources separated with a space
     %e -Executable name
         The highlited name in the executable list. 
   

   @{"Compiler1/2/3" LINK "ls_compiler"}
   @{"Macro1/Run/Debug/Edit/Linker" LINK "ls_other"}
   @{"Macro2" LINK "ls_macro2"}


@endnode


@node "ls_source" "Sources list"

@{b}@{u}Sources list@{ub}@{uu}

list:
 sources

In this list you put the sources in your project.
It is also used to select which source you want to edit/compile etc.

Every sourcefile has the following settings (source settings):

o Compile:
   Never     : compile never
   Always    : compile always
   Prot.bit A: compile when A-bit is cleared, A-bit is setted after
               compiling. Even when Dependant=Always is checked!!
   ObjectDate: compile if sourcefile date is elder than objectfile date

o Compiler:
   Compiler1
   Compiler2
   Compiler3 
  Here you select which compiler script you want to use for THIS source.
  I use this for changing between compile options

@endnode


@node "ls_exec" "executables list"
@{b}@{u}executables list@{ub}@{uu}

list:
  executable

Select as much executables as you want.(at least 1 is recommended)

The name(item) that is highlighted will be used to compile to.
The highlighted item is used to replace the %e in the commandlists.

Be sure you don't include objects or source files in this list!!

For ease you can use the filerequester:
 select the mainsource
 change the name with the string gadget to (example) <mainsource>.exe. 
 DON'T FORGET TO PRESS ENTER!!

@endnode



@node "ls_compiler" "compiler list"
@{b}@{u}compiler1/compiler2/compiler3 lists@{ub}@{uu}

lists:
  compiler1
  compiler2
  compiler3

One of these 3 lists will be executed when compiling a source-file:
Compiling source files:@{"Make" LINK "bt_make"} @{"compile" LINK "bt_compile"}

example:
  compile from %s to %o     ;compile
  rx ErrorsToEditor         ;parse errors to editor
  echo "compiled and errors parsed"
  echo "click close button to continue"

@endnode

@node "ls_other" "other command list"
@{b}@{u}other list@{ub}@{uu}

Lists:
  Macro1
  Run
  Debug
  Edit
  Linker

Commands in these list are executed when you press the equal named @{"buttons" LINK "bt_other"}.

examples:
 run:	run %e
 Debug:	devpac:monam %e
 Edit:	ced %s (better: rx ced_open %s)
 Link:	blink from %l to %e

@endnode
   
@node "ls_macro2" "macro2 list"
@{b}@{u}macro2 list@{ub}@{uu}

list:
 macro2

When you press the @{"Macro2" LINK "bt_macro2"} button, all commands in this list are
executed FOR EVERY SOUCE-FILE.

example:
  c:delete %s

 This will delete all your sourcefiles you specified in the source-list.
 (ok, stupid example)

@endnode

